<h2>Instructor</h2>

<a href=http://www.math.utah.edu/~margalit target=danmargalit>Dan Margalit</a>

<h2>Text</h2>

<i>Abstract Algebra</i>, third edition, by David S. Dummit and Richard M. Foote

<p>

<img src=http://www.math.gatech.edu/~margalit/dummitfoote.JPG>

<h2>Course Description</h2>

This is a graduate level course in abstract algebra covering the fundamentals of groups, rings, vector spaces, modules, and fields.  It will cover roughly the first 14 chapters of the text.

<h2>Class Meetings</h2>

Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays, 9:05-9:55 in Skiles 271.

<h2>Office Hours</h2>

Mondays 10-11 and Wednesdays 11-12.  The teaching assistant for the course, Tianjun Ye, will hold office hours on Thursdays from 2-3 in Skiles 225A.

<h2>Homework</h2>

Homework will be assigned, and due, on a weekly basis.  Collaboration is encouraged, but each student must submit his or her own solutions.

<h2>Exams</h2>

There will be two in-class, closed-book midterm exams, on October 4 and November 15, plus a cumulative take-home final exam during finals week.  

<h2>Grading</h2>

The homework will count for 20&#37; of the final grade, the two midterms 20&#37; each, and the final exam 40&#37;.

<h2>Academic Honesty</h2>

All students are expected to comply with the Georgia Tech honor code

